<worksheet xml:id="activities-partial-orders">

<activity xml:id="activity-partial-orders-compare-Hasse">
	<introduction>
		<p>
		Let <m>F \subseteq \N</m> represent the set of all divisors of <m>30</m>.
		Let <m>A = \{a,b,c\}</m>.
		</p><p>
		<em>Note:</em>
		In <xref ref="activity-partial-orders-compare-Hasse-compare" text="type-local" />
		you will compare your work
		from <xref ref="activity-partial-orders-compare-Hasse-draw-1" text="type-local" />
		and <xref ref="activity-partial-orders-compare-Hasse-draw-2" text="type-local" />,
		so keep your work!
		</p>
	</introduction>
	<task xml:id="activity-partial-orders-compare-Hasse-draw-1"><p>
		Draw the Hasse diagram for the subset partial order <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> on <m>\powset{A}</m>.
	</p></task>
	<task xml:id="activity-partial-orders-compare-Hasse-draw-2"><p>
		Draw the Hasse diagram for the <q>divides</q> partial order <m>\mathord{\mid}</m> on <m>F</m>.
	</p></task>
	<task xml:id="activity-partial-orders-compare-Hasse-compare"><p>
		Compare your two Hasse diagrams.
		Can you devise a function <m>\funcdef{f}{F}{\powset{A}}</m> that would deserve to be called an
		<term>order-preserving correspondence</term> between <m>F</m> and <m>\powset{A}</m>?
	</p></task>
</activity>

<activity><p>
		Suppose <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> is a partial order on a set <m>A</m>.
		Verify that the <xref ref="definition-relations-inverse" text="custom">inverse relation</xref>
		<m>\inv{\partorder}</m> is also a partial order on <m>A</m> by verifying that it is
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-reflexive" text="title" /></term>,
		<term><xref ref="definition-relations-antisymmetric" text="title" /></term>,
		and <term><xref ref="definition-relations-transitive" text="title" /></term>.
</p></activity>

<activity>
	<introduction><p>
		Let <m>A = \{a,b,c,d,e\}</m>.
		Carry out the following steps for each of the scenarios below.
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li> Draw the Hasse diagram for a partial order on <m>A</m> with the requested features. </li>
			<li> In your diagram, identify all maximal/minimal elements. </li>
			<li> Identify all pairs of incomparable elements. </li>
		</ol>
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p> <m>A</m> has both a maximum and a minimum. </p></task>
	<task><p> <m>A</m> has a maximum but no minimum. </p></task>
	<task><p> <m>A</m> has a minimum but no maximum. </p></task>
 	<task><p> <m>A</m> has neither a maximum nor a minimum. </p></task>
</activity>

<activity><p>
	Suppose <m>\mathord{\preceq}</m> is a partial order on the set <m>A = \{0,1,2\}</m> such that <m>1</m> is a maximal element.
	What are the possibilities for the Hasse diagram of <m>\mathord{\preceq}</m>?
</p></activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-partial-orders-prove-maximum-unique">
	<p>
	Using the proper strategy for proving uniqueness
	(see <xref ref="procedure-proof-methods-proving-unique" />),
	prove that if a partially ordered set <m>A</m> has a maximum element,
	then that element is the <em>unique</em> maximum element.
	</p><p>
	How can your proof be modified to show that a minimum element is also unique?
	</p>
</activity>

<activity>
	<p>
	Recall that <m>(a,b)\subseteq \R</m> means an <term>open interval</term> on the real number line:
	<md> (a,b) = \setdef{x \in \R}{a \lt x \lt b} </md>.
	Let <m>\mathord{\le}</m> be the usual <q>less than or equal to</q> total order on the set
	<md> A = (-2,0)\cup(0,2) </md>.
	Consider the subset
	<md> B = \setdef{-\frac{1}{n}}{n \in \N, \, n \ge 1} \subseteq A </md>.
	Determine an upper bound for <m>B</m> in <m>A</m>.
	Then formally prove that <m>B</m> has no <em>least</em> upper bound in <m>A</m> by arguing that every element of <m>A</m> fails the criteria in the definition of <term><xref ref="definition-partial-orders-least-upper-bound" text="title" /></term>.
	</p>
</activity>

</worksheet>
